 
<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(f) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Conditions for authorization of disclosure. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The Chief Counsel, subject to the terms of paragraph (h) of this section, may authorize the disclosure of Customs documents
or the appearance and testimony of a Customs employee if: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) The demanded documents or testimony, in the judgment of the Chief Counsel, are appropriate under the factors specified
in &sect;103.23(a) of this subpart; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) None of the factors specified in &sect;103.23(b) of this subpart exist with respect to the demanded documents
or testimony. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(g) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Limitations on the scope of authorized disclosure. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The Chief Counsel shall, following any necessary consultation with the originating component, authorize the disclosure
of Customs information by a Customs employee without further authorization from Customs officials whenever possible:

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Provided, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
that, when the information demanded relates to that collected, assembled, or prepared in connection with litigation
or an investigation supervised by a Customs Office, Chief Counsel, prior to authorizing such disclosure, seeks to
limit the demand to that which would be consistent with the factors specified in &sect;103.23 of this subpart. The
Chief Counsel shall seek to limit the demand through negotiation with appropriate authority.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(h) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Disclosure of commercial information. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
In the case of a demand for commercial information or commercial documents concerning importations or exportations,
the Chief Counsel or his/her designee shall obtain the authorization of the Assistant Commissioner (Commercial
Operations) or his/her designee prior to the Chief Counsel authorizing the production/disclosure of such documents/information.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;103.23
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
 Factors in determining whether to disclose information pursuant to a demand. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
General considerations. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
In authorizing disclosures pursuant to a demand, the Chief Counsel should consider the following factors: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) Whether the requesting party has demonstrated that the information requested is_
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(i) Relevant and material to the action pending, based on copies of the summons and complaint that are required to be
attached to the subpoena 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
duces tecum 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
or other demand; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) Genuinely necessary to the proceeding, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
i.e., 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
a showing of substantial need has been made; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(iii) Unavailable from other sources; and, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(iv) Reasonable in its scope, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
i.e., 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
the documents, information, or testimony sought are described with particularity. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Whether such disclosure is appropriate under the rules of procedure governing the case or matter in which the demand
arose; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) Whether disclosure or testimony is appropriate under the relevant substantive law concerning privilege. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Circumstances where disclosure will not be made. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Among the demands in response to which disclosure will not be authorized by the Chief Counsel are those demands with
respect to which any of the following factors exist: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) Disclosure would violate a treaty, statute (such as the Privacy Act, 5 U.S.C. 552a, or the income tax laws, 26 U.S.C.
6103 and 7213), or a rule of procedure, such as the grand jury secrecy rule, Fed. R. Crim. Proc. rule 6(e) (18 U.S.C. App.);

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Disclosure would violate a specific regulation; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) Disclosure would reveal classified or confidential information; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) Disclosure would reveal a confidential source or informant; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(5) Disclosure would reveal investigatory records compiled for law enforcement purposes, interfere with enforcement
proceedings, or disclose investigative techniques and procedures; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(6) Disclosure would improperly reveal trade secrets without the owner's consent; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(7) Disclosure relates to documents which were produced by another agency or entity; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(8) Disclosure would unduly interfere with the orderly conduct of Customs business; or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(9) Customs has no interest, records, or other official information regarding the matter in which disclosure is sought.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;103.24
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
 Procedure in the event a decision concerning a demand is not made prior to the time a response to the demand is required.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
If response to a demand is required before the instructions from the Chief Counsel are received, the U.S. Attorney,
his/her assistant, or other appropriate legal representative shall be requested to appear with the Customs employee
upon whom the demand has been made. The U.S. Attorney, his/her assistant, or other appropriate legal representative
shall furnish the court or other authority with a copy of the regulations contained in this subpart, inform the court
or other authority that the demand has been or is being, as the case may be, referred for the prompt consideration of
the Chief Counsel, and shall respectfully request the court or authority to stay the demand pending receipt of the
requested instructions. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

